    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-09-26T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-09-26T12:00:00-05:00" n="495"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d495">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">674.84A/9–2652: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 495<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Israel (<persName corresp="#p_DMB1"
                            type="from">Davis</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d495fn1">Repeated priority to Cairo.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-09-26T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 26, 1952—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>500. Re Cairo <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 763 to Dept<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d495fn2">
                        <ref target="#d492">Document 492</ref>.</note> and request <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 301<note n="3" xml:id="d495fn3">Not
                        printed.</note> (1) Israel’s attitude toward implementing <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> resolutions, (2) Emb’s <pb facs="1052" n="1012"
                        xml:id="pg_1012"/> views <hi rend="italic">bona fides</hi> Israel motives in
                    seeking peace and (3) Israel’s dependability re publicity following is
                    submitted: <list>
                        <item>Point One. FinMin stated in conversation this a.m. Israel had not been
                            and is not now resistant to main <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                            objectives in <gloss target="#t_ME1">ME</gloss>, namely establishment
                            Jewish and Arab States, (2) cessation of hostilities and (3)
                            re-establishment of peaceful relations in <gloss target="#t_ME1"
                                >ME</gloss>. He passed over partition plan resolution as having been
                            superseded by armistice agreements. As to refugees, he asserted
                            repatriation manifestly impracticable but said his govt “will not shirk
                            obligations re settlement and compensation despite difficulties”.
                            Mentioned <gloss target="#t_IG1">IG</gloss> rep had informed <gloss
                                target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> latter’s plan for handling payment of
                            blocked accounts through Barclay’s Bank in London acceptable and that 1
                            million Israel pounds wld be made available as first installment.</item>
                        <item>Point Two. Emb is convinced Israel sincere in desire establish peace
                            with neighbors and become integrated in <gloss target="#t_ME1"
                                >ME</gloss> on basis normal polit, econ and cultural relations.
                            There has been increase in interest taken by <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                                >PriMin</gloss> and other high officials of <gloss target="#t_IG1"
                                >IG</gloss> seeking to improve relations with neighbors, motivated
                            it is believed by realization that without regional peace Israel’s
                            position precarious.</item>
                        <item>Point Three. As to Israel’s propensity seek to influence course of
                            events through press, I agree entirely with view expressed in last para
                            of Emb Cairo <gloss target="#t_desp1">desp</gloss> 405 of Sept 8 that
                            threat of publicity attributed to Israel First <gloss target="#t_Secy1"
                                >Secy</gloss> in Paris is most unfortunate and contemplated to
                            defeat purpose of <gloss target="#t_IG1">IG</gloss> to make progress
                            toward peace with Egypt. I took occasion this morning, therefore, to
                            remind <persName corresp="#p_SM2">Sharett</persName> of our repeated
                            expressions of opinion that untimely publicity on Israel’s part might
                            well wreck any chance of success in important matter of initiating peace
                            talks with Egypt, adding I had reason to believe Egyptian officials
                            extremely sensitive now to danger of any announcements to press that
                            might be so timed as to embarrass them seriously and put end to any
                            possibility of effecting improvement in Israel-Egypt relations that they
                            might otherwise favor.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DMB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
